# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ordinary-differential-equations
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] In the study of differential equations, a **boundary-value problem** is a differential equation subjected to constraints called **boundary conditions**.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] A solution to a boundary value problem is a solution to the differential equation which also satisfies the boundary conditions.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] Boundary value problems arise in several branches of physics as any physical differential equation will have them.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] Problems involving the wave equation, such as the determination of normal modes, are often stated as boundary value problems.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] A large class of important boundary value problems are the Sturm–Liouville problems.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] The analysis of these problems, in the linear case, involves the eigenfunctions of a differential operator.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] To be useful in applications, a boundary value problem should be well posed.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] This means that given the input to the problem there exists a unique solution, which depends continuously on the input.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] Much theoretical work in the field of partial differential equations is devoted to proving that boundary value problems arising from scientific and engineering applications are in fact well-posed.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] Among the earliest boundary value problems to be studied is the Dirichlet problem, of finding the harmonic functions (solutions to Laplace's equation); the solution was given by the Dirichlet's principle.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] Boundary value problems are similar to initial value problems.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] A **boundary value** is a data value that corresponds to a minimum or maximum input, internal, or output value specified for a system or component.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] For example, if the independent variable is time over the domain [0,1], a boundary value problem would specify values for $y(t)$ at both $t=0$ and $t=1$ , whereas an initial value problem would specify a value of $y(t)$ and $y'(t)$ at time $t=0$ .
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] Finding the temperature at all points of an iron bar with one end kept at absolute zero and the other end at the freezing point of water would be a boundary value problem.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] If the problem is dependent on both space and time, one could specify the value of the problem at a given point for all time or at a given time for all space.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] The 3 standard classes of conditions are Dirichlet, Neumann and Cauchy or Robin, with also mixed, boundary as infinity.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] Summary of boundary conditions for the unknown function, y , constants $c_{0}$ and $c_{1}$ specified by the boundary conditions, and known scalar functions f and g specified by the boundary conditions.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] A type 1 boundary condition, Dirichlet boundary condition, specifies the value of the function itself.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] For example, if one end of an iron rod is held at absolute zero, then the value of the problem would be known at that point in space.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] A type 2 boundary condition, Neumann boundary condition, specifies the value of the normal derivative of the function.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] For example, if there is a heater at one end of an iron rod, then energy would be added at a constant rate but the actual temperature would not be known.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] A type 3 boundary condition is the Robin condition.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] If the boundary has the form of a curve or surface that gives a value to the normal derivative and the variable itself then it is a Cauchy boundary condition.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] A type 0 boundary condition has no physical boundary.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] Aside from the boundary condition, boundary value problems are also classified according to the type of differential operator involved.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] For an elliptic operator, one discusses elliptic boundary value problems.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] For a hyperbolic operator, one discusses hyperbolic boundary value problems.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] These categories are further subdivided into linear and various nonlinear types.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] In electrostatics, a common problem is to find a function which describes the electric potential of a given region.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] If the region does not contain charge, the potential must be a solution to Laplace's equation (a so-called harmonic function).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] The boundary conditions in this case are the Interface conditions for electromagnetic fields.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/boundary-value-problem] If there is no current density in the region, it is also possible to define a magnetic scalar potential using a similar procedure.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/initial-value-problem] In calculus, an **initial value problem** (**IVP**) is an ordinary differential equation together with an initial condition which specifies the value of the unknown function at a given point in the domain.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/initial-value-problem] Modeling a system in physics or other sciences frequently amounts to solving an initial value problem.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/initial-value-problem] In that context, the IVP is a differential equation which specifies how the system evolves with time plus the initial conditions of the problem.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/initial-value-problem] In higher dimensions, the differential equation is replaced with a family of equations $y_{i}'(t)=f_{i}(t,y_{1}(t),y_{2}(t),\dotsc )$ , and $y(t)$ is viewed as the vector $(y_{1}(t),\dotsc ,y_{n}(t))$ , most commonly associated with the position in space.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/initial-value-problem] More generally, the unknown function y can take values on infinite dimensional spaces, such as Banach spaces or spaces of distributions.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/initial-value-problem] Initial value problems are extended to higher orders by treating the derivatives in the same way as an independent function, e.g. $y''(t)=f(t,y(t),y'(t))$ .
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/initial-value-problem] For this second-order differential equation, two initial conditions are needed, for example the numerical values of $y(0)$ and $y'(0)$ .
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/initial-value-problem] The Picard–Lindelöf theorem guarantees a unique solution on some interval containing *t*0 if *f* is continuous on a region containing *t*0 and *y*0 and satisfies the Lipschitz condition on the variable *y*.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/initial-value-problem] The proof of this theorem proceeds by reformulating the problem as an equivalent integral equation.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/initial-value-problem] The integral can be considered an operator which maps one function into another, such that the solution is a fixed point of the operator.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/initial-value-problem] The Banach fixed point theorem is then invoked to show that there exists a unique fixed point, which is the solution of the initial value problem.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/initial-value-problem] An older proof of the Picard–Lindelöf theorem constructs a sequence of functions which converge to the solution of the integral equation, and thus, the solution of the initial value problem.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/initial-value-problem] Such a construction is sometimes called "Picard's method" or "the method of successive approximations".
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/initial-value-problem] This version is essentially a special case of the Banach fixed point theorem.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/initial-value-problem] Hiroshi Okamura obtained a necessary and sufficient condition for the solution of an initial value problem to be unique.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/initial-value-problem] This condition has to do with the existence of a Lyapunov function for the system.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/initial-value-problem] In some situations, the function *f* is not of class *C*1, or even Lipschitz, so the usual result guaranteeing the local existence of a unique solution does not apply.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/initial-value-problem] The Peano existence theorem however proves that even for *f* merely continuous, solutions are guaranteed to exist locally in time; the problem is that there is no guarantee of uniqueness.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/initial-value-problem] The result may be found in Coddington & Levinson (1955, Theorem 1.3) or Robinson (2001, Theorem 2.6).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/initial-value-problem] An even more general result is the Carathéodory existence theorem, which proves existence for some discontinuous functions *f*.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/initial-value-problem] We are trying to find a formula for $y(t)$ that satisfies these two equations.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/initial-value-problem] Now integrate both sides with respect to t (this introduces an unknown constant B ).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/initial-value-problem] and $y(0)=2+0+1=3$ , so the given function satisfies the ODE and the initial condition.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/initial-value-problem] The function is differentiable everywhere and continuous, while satisfying the differential equation as well as the initial value problem.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/initial-value-problem] Thus, this is an example of such a problem with infinite number of solutions.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The functions are often denoted using a lowercase symbol for the time-domain function and the corresponding uppercase symbol for the frequency-domain function, e.g. $x(t)$ and ⁠ $X(s)$ ⁠.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The transform is useful for converting differentiation and integration in the time domain into the algebraic operations multiplication and division in the Laplace domain (analogous to how logarithms are useful for simplifying multiplication and division into addition and subtraction).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Once solved, the inverse Laplace transform can be used to transform it to the original domain.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] This is often aided by referencing tables such as that given below.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform is defined (for suitable functions ⁠ f ⁠) by the integral ${\mathcal {L}}\{f\}(s)=\int _{0}^{\infty }f(t)e^{-st}\,dt,$ where ⁠ s ⁠ is a complex number.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform is related to many other transforms.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] It is essentially the same as the Mellin transform and is closely related to the Fourier transform.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Unlike for the Fourier transform, the Laplace transform of a function is often an analytic function, meaning that it can be expressed as a power series that converges locally, the coefficients of which represent the moments of the original function.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Moreover, the techniques of complex analysis, especially contour integrals, can be used for simplifying calculations.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform is named after mathematician and astronomer Pierre-Simon, Marquis de Laplace, who used a similar transform in his work on probability theory.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Laplace wrote extensively about the use of generating functions (1814), and the integral form of the Laplace transform evolved naturally as a result.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Laplace's use of generating functions was similar to what is now known as the z-transform, and he gave little attention to the continuous variable case which was discussed by Niels Henrik Abel.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] From 1744, Leonhard Euler investigated integrals of the form $z=\int X(x)e^{ax}\,dx\quad {\text{ and }}\quad z=\int X(x)x^{A}\,dx$ as solutions of differential equations, introducing in particular the gamma function.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Joseph-Louis Lagrange was an admirer of Euler and, in his work on integrating probability density functions, investigated expressions of the form $\int X(x)e^{-ax}a^{x}\,dx,$ which resembles a Laplace transform.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] These types of integrals seem first to have attracted Laplace's attention in 1782, where he was following in the spirit of Euler in using the integrals themselves as solutions of equations.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] However, in 1785, Laplace took the critical step forward when, rather than simply looking for a solution in the form of an integral, he started to apply the transforms in the sense that was later to become popular.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] He used an integral of the form $\int x^{s}\varphi (x)\,dx,$ akin to a Mellin transform, to transform the whole of a difference equation, in order to look for solutions of the transformed equation.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] He then went on to apply the Laplace transform in the same way and started to derive some of its properties, beginning to appreciate its potential power.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Laplace also recognised that Joseph Fourier's method of Fourier series for solving the diffusion equation could only apply to a limited region of space, because those solutions were periodic.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] In 1809, Laplace applied his transform to find solutions that diffused indefinitely in space.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] In 1821, Cauchy developed an operational calculus for the Laplace transform that could be used to study linear differential equations in much the same way the transform is now used in basic engineering.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] This method was popularized, and perhaps rediscovered, by Oliver Heaviside around the turn of the century.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Bernhard Riemann used the Laplace transform in his 1859 paper *On the number of primes less than a given magnitude*, in which he also developed the inversion theorem.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Riemann used the Laplace transform to develop the functional equation of the Riemann zeta function, and his method is still used to relate the modular transformation law of the Jacobi theta function, which is readily proved via Poisson summation, to the functional equation.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Hjalmar Mellin was among the first to study the Laplace transform rigorously in the Karl Weierstrass school of analysis, and apply it to the study of differential equations and special functions, at the turn of the 20th century.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] At around the same time, Heaviside was busy with his operational calculus.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Thomas Joannes Stieltjes considered a generalization of the Laplace transform connected to his work on moments.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Other contributors in this time period included Mathias Lerch, Oliver Heaviside, and Thomas Bromwich.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] In 1929, Vannevar Bush and Norbert Wiener published *Operational Circuit Analysis* as a text for engineering analysis of electrical circuits, applying both Fourier transforms and operational calculus, and in which they included one of the first predecessors of the modern table of Laplace transforms.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] In 1934, Raymond Paley and Norbert Wiener published the important work *Fourier transforms in the complex domain*, about what is now called the Laplace transform (see below).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Also during the 30s, the Laplace transform was instrumental in Godfrey Harold Hardy and John Edensor Littlewood's study of tauberian theorems, and this application was later expounded on by Widder (1941), who developed other aspects of the theory such as a new method for inversion.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Edward Charles Titchmarsh wrote the influential *Introduction to the theory of the Fourier integral* (1937).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The current widespread use of the transform (mainly in engineering) came about during and soon after World War II, replacing the earlier Heaviside operational calculus.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The advantages of the Laplace transform had been emphasized by Gustav Doetsch.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] where s is a complex frequency-domain parameter ${\textstyle s=\sigma +i\omega }$ with real numbers σ and ω.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] An alternate notation for the Laplace transform is ${\mathcal {L}}\{f\}$ instead of *F*.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] This is often written, especially in engineering settings, as ⁠ $F(s)={\mathcal {L}}\{f(t)\}$ ⁠, with the understanding that the dummy variable t does not appear in the function ⁠ $F(s)$ ⁠.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The meaning of the integral depends on types of functions of interest.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] A necessary condition for existence of the integral is that f must be locally integrable on [0, ∞).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] For locally integrable functions that decay at infinity or are of exponential type (⁠ $\vert f(t)\vert \leq Ae^{B\vert t\vert }$ ⁠), the integral can be understood to be a (proper) Lebesgue integral.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] However, for many applications it is necessary to regard it as a conditionally convergent improper integral at ∞.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Still more generally, the integral can be understood in a weak sense, and this is dealt with below.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] An important special case is where μ is a probability measure, for example, the Dirac delta function.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] In operational calculus, the Laplace transform of a measure is often treated as though the measure came from a probability density function f.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] This limit emphasizes that any point mass located at 0 is entirely captured by the Laplace transform.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Although with the Lebesgue integral, it is not necessary to take such a limit, it does appear more naturally in connection with the Laplace–Stieltjes transform.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] When one says "the Laplace transform" without qualification, the unilateral or one-sided transform is usually intended.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform can be alternatively defined as the *bilateral Laplace transform*, or two-sided Laplace transform, by extending the limits of integration to be the entire real axis.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] If that is done, the common unilateral transform becomes a special case of the bilateral transform, where the definition of the function being transformed includes being multiplied by the Heaviside step function.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] An alternate notation for the bilateral Laplace transform is ⁠ ${\mathcal {B}}\{f\}$ ⁠, instead of F.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Two integrable functions have the same Laplace transform only if they differ on a set of Lebesgue measure zero.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] This means that, on the range of the transform, there is an inverse transform.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] In fact, besides integrable functions, the Laplace transform is a one-to-one mapping from one function space into another in many other function spaces as well, although there is usually no easy characterization of the range.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Typical function spaces in which this is true include the spaces of bounded continuous functions, the space *L*∞(0, ∞), or more generally tempered distributions on (0, ∞).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform is also defined and injective for suitable spaces of tempered distributions.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] In these cases, the image of the Laplace transform lives in a space of analytic functions in the region of convergence.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] where γ is a real number so that the contour path of integration is in the region of convergence of *F*(*s*).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] In most applications, the contour can be closed, allowing the use of the residue theorem.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] An alternative formula for the inverse Laplace transform is given by Post's inversion formula.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The limit here is interpreted in the weak-* topology.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] In practice, it is typically more convenient to decompose a Laplace transform into known transforms of functions obtained from a table and construct the inverse by inspection.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] In pure and applied probability, the Laplace transform is defined as an expected value.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] If X is a random variable with probability density function f, then the Laplace transform of f is given by the expectation ${\mathcal {L}}\{f\}(s)=\operatorname {E} \left[e^{-sX}\right],$ where $\operatorname {E} [r]$ is the expectation of random variable ⁠ r ⁠.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] By convention, this is referred to as the Laplace transform of the random variable X itself.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Here, replacing s by −*t* gives the moment generating function of X.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform has applications throughout probability theory, including first passage times of stochastic processes such as Markov chains, and renewal theory.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform can be alternatively defined in a purely algebraic manner by applying a field of fractions construction to the convolution ring of functions on the positive half-line.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The resulting space of abstract operators is exactly equivalent to Laplace space, but in this construction the forward and reverse transforms never need to be explicitly defined (avoiding the related difficulties with proving convergence).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] If *f* is a locally integrable function (or more generally a Borel measure locally of bounded variation), then the Laplace transform *F*(*s*) of *f* converges provided that the limit $\lim _{R\to \infty }\int _{0}^{R}f(t)e^{-st}\,dt$ exists.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform converges absolutely if the integral $\int _{0}^{\infty }\left|f(t)e^{-st}\right|\,dt$ exists as a proper Lebesgue integral.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform is usually understood as conditionally convergent, meaning that it converges in the former but not in the latter sense.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The set of values for which *F*(*s*) converges absolutely is either of the form Re(*s*) > *a* or Re(*s*) ≥ *a*, where *a* is an extended real constant with −∞ ≤ *a* ≤ ∞ (a consequence of the dominated convergence theorem).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The constant *a* is known as the abscissa of absolute convergence, and depends on the growth behavior of *f*(*t*).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Analogously, the two-sided transform converges absolutely in a strip of the form *a* < Re(*s*) < *b*, and possibly including the lines Re(*s*) = *a* or Re(*s*) = *b*.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The subset of values of *s* for which the Laplace transform converges absolutely is called the region of absolute convergence, or the domain of absolute convergence.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] In the two-sided case, it is sometimes called the strip of absolute convergence.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform is analytic in the region of absolute convergence: this is a consequence of Fubini's theorem and Morera's theorem.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Similarly, the set of values for which *F*(*s*) converges (conditionally or absolutely) is known as the region of conditional convergence, or simply the **region of convergence** (ROC).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] If the Laplace transform converges (conditionally) at *s* = *s*0, then it automatically converges for all *s* with Re(*s*) > Re(*s*0).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Therefore, the region of convergence is a half-plane of the form Re(*s*) > *a*, possibly including some points of the boundary line Re(*s*) = *a*.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] That is, *F*(*s*) can effectively be expressed, in the region of convergence, as the absolutely convergent Laplace transform of some other function.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] There are several Paley–Wiener theorems concerning the relationship between the decay properties of *f*, and the properties of the Laplace transform within the region of convergence.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] In engineering applications, a function corresponding to a linear time-invariant (LTI) system is *stable* if every bounded input produces a bounded output.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] This is equivalent to the absolute convergence of the Laplace transform of the impulse response function in the region Re(*s*) ≥ 0.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] As a result, LTI systems are stable, provided that the poles of the Laplace transform of the impulse response function have negative real part.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] This ROC is used in knowing about the causality and stability of a system.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform's key property is that it converts differentiation and integration in the time domain into multiplication and division by *s* in the Laplace domain.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Thus, the Laplace variable *s* is also known as an *operator variable* in the Laplace domain: either the *derivative operator* or (for *s*−1) the *integration operator*.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] decompositions (or other difficult algebra).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] ), then the behaviour of this formula is undefined.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform can be viewed as a continuous analogue of a power series.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] If *a*(*n*) is a discrete function of a positive integer *n*, then the power series associated to *a*(*n*) is the series $\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }a(n)x^{n}$ where *x* is a real variable (see *Z-transform*).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Replacing summation over *n* with integration over *t*, a continuous version of the power series becomes $\int _{0}^{\infty }f(t)x^{t}\,dt$ where the discrete function *a*(*n*) is replaced by the continuous one *f*(*t*).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] For this to converge for, say, all bounded functions *f*, it is necessary to require that ln *x* < 0.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] In other words, the Laplace transform is a continuous analog of a power series, in which the discrete parameter *n* is replaced by the continuous parameter *t*, and *x* is replaced by *e*−*s*.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Analogously to a power series, if ⁠ $a(n)=O(\rho ^{-n})$ ⁠, then the power series converges to an analytic function in ⁠ $\vert x\vert <\rho$ ⁠, if ⁠ $f(t)=O(e^{-\sigma t})$ ⁠, the Laplace transform converges to an analytic function for ⁠ $\Re (s)>\sigma$ ⁠.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] It is often convenient to use the differentiation property of the Laplace transform to find the transform of a function's derivative.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The above formula is a variation of integration by parts, with the operators ${\frac {d}{dx}}$ and $\int \,dx$ being replaced by ${\mathcal {L}}$ and ⁠ ${\mathcal {L}}^{-1}$ ⁠.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] By plugging in $({\mathcal {L}}f)(x)=\int _{0}^{\infty }f(s)e^{-sx}\,ds$ the left-hand side turns into: $\int _{0}^{\infty }\int _{0}^{\infty }f(s)g(x)e^{-sx}\,ds\,dx,$ but assuming Fubini's theorem holds, by reversing the order of integration we get the wanted right-hand side.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] This method can be used to compute integrals that would otherwise be difficult to compute using elementary methods of real calculus.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The function *g* is assumed to be of bounded variation.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] then the Laplace–Stieltjes transform of g and the Laplace transform of f coincide.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] In general, the Laplace–Stieltjes transform is the Laplace transform of the Stieltjes measure associated to g.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] So in practice, the only distinction between the two transforms is that the Laplace transform is thought of as operating on the density function of the measure, whereas the Laplace–Stieltjes transform is thought of as operating on its cumulative distribution function.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Let f be a complex-valued Lebesgue integrable function supported on ⁠ $[0,\infty )$ ⁠, and let $F(s)={\mathcal {L}}f(s)$ be its Laplace transform.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Then, within the region of convergence, we have $F(\sigma +i\tau )=\int _{0}^{\infty }f(t)e^{-\sigma t}e^{-i\tau t}\,dt,$ which is the Fourier transform of the function ⁠ $f(t)e^{-\sigma t}$ ⁠.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Indeed, the Fourier transform is a special case (under certain conditions) of the bilateral Laplace transform.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The main difference is that the Fourier transform of a function is a complex function of a *real* variable (frequency ⁠ $\tau$ ⁠), the Laplace transform of a function is a complex function of a *complex* variable (damping factor $\sigma$ and frequency ⁠ $\tau$ ⁠).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform is usually restricted to transformation of functions of *t* with *t* ≥ 0.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] A consequence of this restriction is that the Laplace transform of a function is a holomorphic function of the variable *s*.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Unlike the Fourier transform, the Laplace transform of a distribution is generally a well-behaved function.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Techniques of complex variables can also be used to directly study Laplace transforms.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] As a holomorphic function, the Laplace transform has a power series representation.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] This power series expresses a function as a linear superposition of moments of the function.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] This perspective has applications in probability theory.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] This convention of the Fourier transform (⁠ ${\hat {f}}_{3}(\omega )$ ⁠ in *Fourier transform § Other conventions*) requires a factor of ⁠1/2*π*⁠ on the inverse Fourier transform.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] This relationship between the Laplace and Fourier transforms is often used to determine the frequency spectrum of a signal or dynamical system.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The above relation is valid as stated if and only if the region of convergence (ROC) of *F*(*s*) contains the imaginary axis, *σ* = 0.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] As *s* = *iω*0 is a pole of *F*(*s*), substituting *s* = *iω* in *F*(*s*) does not yield the Fourier transform of *f*(*t*)*u*(*t*), which contains terms proportional to the Dirac delta functions *δ*(*ω* ± *ω*0).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] However, a relation of the form $\lim _{\sigma \to 0^{+}}F(\sigma +i\omega )={\hat {f}}(\omega )$ holds under much weaker conditions.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] For instance, this holds for the above example provided that the limit is understood as a weak limit of measures (see vague topology).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] General conditions relating the limit of the Laplace transform of a function on the boundary to the Fourier transform take the form of Paley–Wiener theorems.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The Mellin transform and its inverse are related to the two-sided Laplace transform by a change of variables.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] This is the precise definition of the unilateral Z-transform of the discrete function *x*[*n*] $X(z)=\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }x[n]z^{-n}$ with the substitution of *z* → *e**sT*.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The similarity between the Z- and Laplace transforms is expanded upon in the theory of time scale calculus.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The integral form of the Borel transform $F(s)=\int _{0}^{\infty }f(z)e^{-sz}\,dz$ is a special case of the Laplace transform for *f* an entire function of exponential type, meaning that $|f(z)|\leq Ae^{B|z|}$ for some constants *A* and *B*.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The generalized Borel transform allows a different weighting function to be used, rather than the exponential function, to transform functions not of exponential type.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Nachbin's theorem gives necessary and sufficient conditions for the Borel transform to be well defined.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Since an ordinary Laplace transform can be written as a special case of a two-sided transform, and since the two-sided transform can be written as the sum of two one-sided transforms, the theory of the Laplace-, Fourier-, Mellin-, and Z-transforms are at bottom the same subject.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] However, a different point of view and different characteristic problems are associated with each of these four major integral transforms.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The following table provides Laplace transforms for many common functions of a single variable.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] For definitions and explanations, see the *Explanatory Notes* at the end of the table.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Using this linearity, and various trigonometric, hyperbolic, and complex number (etc.) properties and/or identities, some Laplace transforms can be obtained from others more quickly than by using the definition directly.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The unilateral Laplace transform takes as input a function whose time domain is the non-negative reals, which is why all of the time domain functions in the table below are multiples of the Heaviside step function, *u*(*t*).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The entries of the table that involve a time delay *τ* are required to be causal (meaning that *τ* > 0).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] A causal system is a system where the impulse response *h*(*t*) is zero for all time t prior to *t* = 0.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] In general, the region of convergence for causal systems is not the same as that of anticausal systems.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform is often used in circuit analysis by conversions to the *s*-domain of circuit elements.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Circuit elements can be transformed into impedances, very similar to phasor impedances.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] Note that the resistor is exactly the same in the time domain and the *s*-domain.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The sources are put in if there are initial conditions on the circuit elements.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] For example, if a capacitor has an initial voltage across it, or if the inductor has an initial current through it, the sources inserted in the *s*-domain account for that.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p01] The equivalents for current and voltage sources are derived from the transformations in the table above.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] The Laplace transform is used frequently in engineering and physics; the output of a linear time-invariant system can be calculated by convolving its unit impulse response with the input signal.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] Performing this calculation in Laplace space turns the convolution into a multiplication; the latter being easier to solve because of its algebraic form.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] For more information, see control theory.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] The Laplace transform is invertible on a large class of functions.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] Given a mathematical or functional description of an input or output to a system, the Laplace transform provides an alternative functional description that often simplifies the process of analyzing the behavior of the system, or in synthesizing a new system based on a set of specifications.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] The Laplace transform can also be used to solve differential equations and is used extensively in mechanical engineering and electrical engineering.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] The Laplace transform reduces a linear differential equation to an algebraic equation, which can then be solved by the formal rules of algebra.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] The original differential equation can then be solved by applying the inverse Laplace transform.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] English electrical engineer Oliver Heaviside first proposed a similar scheme, although without using the Laplace transform; and the resulting operational calculus is credited as the Heaviside calculus.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] In the limit ⁠ $s\rightarrow 0$ ⁠, one gets $\int _{0}^{\infty }{\frac {f(t)}{t}}\,dt=\int _{0}^{\infty }F(p)\,dp,$ provided that the interchange of limits can be justified.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] This is often possible as a consequence of the final value theorem.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] Even when the interchange cannot be justified the calculation can be suggestive.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] In the theory of electrical circuits, the current flow in a capacitor is proportional to the capacitance and rate of change in the electrical potential (with equations as for the SI unit system).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] Using this definition and the previous equation, we find: $Z(s)={\frac {1}{sC}},$ which is the correct expression for the complex impedance of a capacitor.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] In addition, the Laplace transform has large applications in control theory.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] The unknown constants *P* and *R* are the residues located at the corresponding poles of the transfer function.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] Each residue represents the relative contribution of that singularity to the transfer function's overall shape.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] By the residue theorem, the inverse Laplace transform depends only upon the poles and their residues.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] The same result can be achieved using the convolution property as if the system is a series of filters with transfer functions 1/(*s* + *α*) and 1/(*s* + *β*).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] In statistical mechanics, the Laplace transform of the density of states $g(E)$ defines the partition function.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] When independent information on the structure of an object is available, the inverse Laplace transform method has been found to be in good agreement.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] Consider a random walk, with steps $\{+1,-1\}$ occurring with probabilities ⁠ $p,q=1-p$ ⁠.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] Suppose also that the time step is a Poisson process, with parameter ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] They are thus of importance in asymptotic formulae of probability and statistics, where often the spectral side has asymptotics that are simpler to infer.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] Two Tauberian theorems of note are the Hardy–Littlewood Tauberian theorem and Wiener's Tauberian theorem.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] Let ⁠ $A(x)$ ⁠ be a non-negative, monotonic nondecreasing function of ⁠ x ⁠, defined for ⁠ $0\leq x<\infty$ ⁠.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] Suppose that $f(s)=\int _{0}^{\infty }A(x)e^{-xs}\,dx$ converges for ⁠ $\Re (s)>1$ ⁠ to the function ⁠ $f(s)$ ⁠ and that, for some non-negative number ⁠ c ⁠, $f(s)-{\frac {c}{s-1}}$ has an extension as a continuous function for ⁠ $\Re (s)\geq 1$ ⁠.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] Then the limit as ⁠ x ⁠ goes to infinity of ⁠ $e^{-x}A(x)$ ⁠ is equal to ⁠ c ⁠.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/laplace-transform-p02] This statement can be applied in particular to the logarithmic derivative of Riemann zeta function, and thus provides an extremely short way to prove the prime number theorem.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] Such an equation is an ordinary differential equation (ODE).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] A *linear differential equation* may also be a linear partial differential equation (PDE), if the unknown function depends on several variables, and the derivatives that appear in the equation are partial derivatives.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] A linear differential equation or a system of linear equations such that the associated homogeneous equations have constant coefficients may be **solved by quadrature**, which means that the solutions may be expressed in terms of integrals.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] This is also true for a linear equation of order one, with non-constant coefficients.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] An equation of order two or higher with non-constant coefficients cannot, in general, be solved by quadrature.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] For order two, Kovacic's algorithm allows deciding whether there are solutions in terms of integrals, and computing them if any.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] The solutions of homogeneous linear differential equations with polynomial coefficients are called holonomic functions.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] This class of functions is stable under sums, products, differentiation, integration, and contains many usual functions and special functions such as exponential function, logarithm, sine, cosine, inverse trigonometric functions, error function, Bessel functions and hypergeometric functions.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] Their representation by the defining differential equation and initial conditions allows making algorithmic (on these functions) most operations of calculus, such as computation of antiderivatives, limits, asymptotic expansion, and numerical evaluation to any precision, with a certified error bound.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] The highest order of derivation that appears in a (linear) differential equation is the *order* of the equation.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] The term *b*(*x*), which does not depend on the unknown function and its derivatives, is sometimes called the *constant term* of the equation (by analogy with algebraic equations), even when this term is a non-constant function.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] If the constant term is the zero function, then the differential equation is said to be *homogeneous*, as it is a homogeneous polynomial in the unknown function and its derivatives.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] The equation obtained by replacing, in a linear differential equation, the constant term by the zero function is the *associated homogeneous equation*.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] A differential equation has *constant coefficients* if only constant functions appear as coefficients in the associated homogeneous equation.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] A *solution* of a differential equation is a function that satisfies the equation.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] The solutions of a homogeneous linear differential equation form a vector space.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] In the ordinary case, this vector space has a finite dimension, equal to the order of the equation.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] All solutions of a linear differential equation are found by adding to a particular solution any solution of the associated homogeneous equation.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] A *basic differential operator* of order i is a mapping that maps any differentiable function to its ith derivative, or, in the case of several variables, to one of its partial derivatives of order i.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] It is commonly denoted ${\frac {d^{i}}{dx^{i}}}$ in the case of univariate functions, and ${\frac {\partial ^{i_{1}+\cdots +i_{n}}}{\partial x_{1}^{i_{1}}\cdots \partial x_{n}^{i_{n}}}}$ in the case of functions of n variables.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] The basic differential operators include the derivative of order 0, which is the identity mapping.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] A **linear differential operator** (abbreviated, in this article, as *linear operator* or, simply, *operator*) is a linear combination of basic differential operators, with differentiable functions as coefficients.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] Let L be a linear differential operator.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] The application of L to a function f is usually denoted *Lf* or *Lf*(*X*), if one needs to specify the variable (this must not be confused with a multiplication).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] A linear differential operator is a linear operator, since it maps sums to sums and the product by a scalar to the product by the same scalar.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] They form also a free module over the ring of differentiable functions.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] There may be several variants to this notation; in particular the variable of differentiation may appear explicitly or not in y and the right-hand and of the equation, such as *Ly*(*x*) = *b*(*x*) or *Ly* = *b*.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] The *kernel* of a linear differential operator is its kernel as a linear mapping, that is the vector space of the solutions of the (homogeneous) differential equation *Ly* = 0.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] Typically, the hypotheses of Carathéodory's theorem are satisfied in an interval I, if the functions *b*, *a*0, ..., *a**n* are continuous in I, and there is a positive real number k such that |*a**n*(*x*)| > *k* for every x in I.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] A homogeneous linear differential equation has *constant coefficients* if it has the form $a_{0}y+a_{1}y'+a_{2}y''+\cdots +a_{n}y^{(n)}=0$ where *a*1, ..., *a**n* are (real or complex) numbers.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] In other words, it has constant coefficients if it is defined by a linear operator with constant coefficients.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] The study of these differential equations with constant coefficients dates back to Leonhard Euler, who introduced the exponential function $e^{x}$ , which is the unique solution of the equation $f'=f$ , such that $f(0)=1$ .
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] It follows that the nth derivative of $e^{cx}$ is $c^{n}e^{cx}$ , and this allows solving homogeneous linear differential equations rather easily.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] Let $a_{0}y+a_{1}y'+a_{2}y''+\cdots +a_{n}y^{(n)}=0$ be a homogeneous linear differential equation with constant coefficients (that is *a*0, ..., *a**n* are real or complex numbers).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] When these roots are all distinct, one has n distinct solutions that are not necessarily real, even if the coefficients of the equation are real.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] These solutions can be shown to be linearly independent, by considering the Vandermonde determinant of the values of these solutions at *x* = 0, ..., *n* – 1.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] Together they form a basis of the vector space of solutions of the differential equation (that is, the kernel of the differential operator).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] In the case where the characteristic polynomial has only simple roots, the preceding provides a complete basis of the solutions vector space.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] In the case of multiple roots, more linearly independent solutions are needed for having a basis.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] These have the form $x^{k}e^{\alpha x},$ where k is a nonnegative integer, α is a root of the characteristic polynomial of multiplicity m, and *k* < *m*.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] For proving that these functions are solutions, one may remark that if α is a root of the characteristic polynomial of multiplicity m, the characteristic polynomial may be factored as *P*(*t*)(*t* − *α*)*m*.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] Thus, applying the differential operator of the equation is equivalent with applying first m times the operator ${\textstyle {\frac {d}{dx}}-\alpha }$ , and then the operator that has P as characteristic polynomial.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] and thus one gets zero after *k* + 1 application of ${\textstyle {\frac {d}{dx}}-\alpha }$ .
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] As, by the fundamental theorem of algebra, the sum of the multiplicities of the roots of a polynomial equals the degree of the polynomial, the number of above solutions equals the order of the differential equation, and these solutions form a basis of the vector space of the solutions.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] In the common case where the coefficients of the equation are real, it is generally more convenient to have a basis of the solutions consisting of real-valued functions.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] Such a basis may be obtained from the preceding basis by remarking that, if *a* + *ib* is a root of the characteristic polynomial, then *a* – *ib* is also a root, of the same multiplicity.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] If a and b are real, there are three cases for the solutions, depending on the discriminant *D* = *a*2 − 4*b*.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] In all three cases, the general solution depends on two arbitrary constants *c*1 and *c*2.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] Finding the solution *y*(*x*) satisfying *y*(0) = *d*1 and *y*′(0) = *d*2, one equates the values of the above general solution at 0 and its derivative there to *d*1 and *d*2, respectively.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] This results in a linear system of two linear equations in the two unknowns *c*1 and *c*2.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] Solving this system gives the solution for a so-called Cauchy problem, in which the values at 0 for the solution of the DEQ and its derivative are specified.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] There are several methods for solving such an equation.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] The best method depends on the nature of the function f that makes the equation non-homogeneous.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] If f is a linear combination of exponential and sinusoidal functions, then the exponential response formula may be used.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] If, more generally, f is a linear combination of functions of the form *x**n**e**ax*, *x**n* cos(*ax*), and *x**n* sin(*ax*), where n is a nonnegative integer, and a a constant (which need not be the same in each term), then the method of undetermined coefficients may be used.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] Still more general, the annihilator method applies when f satisfies a homogeneous linear differential equation, typically, a holonomic function.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] The most general method is the variation of constants, which is presented here.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] The method of variation of constants takes its name from the following idea.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] Instead of considering *u*1, ..., *u**n* as constants, they can be considered as unknown functions that have to be determined for making y a solution of the non-homogeneous equation.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] This equation and the above ones with 0 as left-hand side form a system of n linear equations in *u*′1, ..., *u*′*n* whose coefficients are known functions (f, the *y*i, and their derivatives).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] This system can be solved by any method of linear algebra.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] As antiderivatives are defined up to the addition of a constant, one finds again that the general solution of the non-homogeneous equation is the sum of an arbitrary solution and the general solution of the associated homogeneous equation.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] *g*(*x*) = 0, one may rewrite and integrate: ${\frac {y'}{y}}=f,\qquad \log y=k+F,$ where k is an arbitrary constant of integration and $F=\textstyle \int f\,dx$ is any antiderivative of f.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] Thus, the general solution of the homogeneous equation is $y=ce^{F},$ where *c* = *e**k* is an arbitrary constant.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] For the general non-homogeneous equation, it is useful to multiply both sides of the equation by the reciprocal *e*−*F* of a solution of the homogeneous equation.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] We want left had side to be a total derivative: $d(h(x)y(x))/dx$ .
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] A system of linear differential equations consists of several linear differential equations that involve several unknown functions.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] In general one restricts the study to systems such that the number of unknown functions equals the number of equations.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] An arbitrary linear ordinary differential equation and a system of such equations can be converted into a first order system of linear differential equations by adding variables for all but the highest order derivatives.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] A linear system of the first order, which has n unknown functions and n differential equations may normally be solved for the derivatives of the unknown functions.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] If it is not the case this is a differential-algebraic system, and this is a different theory.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] The solving method is similar to that of a single first order linear differential equations, but with complications stemming from noncommutativity of matrix multiplication.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] Let $\mathbf {u} '=A\mathbf {u} .$ be the homogeneous equation associated to the above matrix equation.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] Its solutions form a vector space of dimension n, and are therefore the columns of a square matrix of functions ⁠ $U(x)$ ⁠, whose determinant is not the zero function.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] If *n* = 1, or A is a matrix of constants, or, more generally, if A commutes with its antiderivative ⁠ $\textstyle B=\int Adx$ ⁠, then one may choose U equal the exponential of B.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] In fact, in these cases, one has ${\frac {d}{dx}}\exp(B)=A\exp(B).$ In the general case there is no closed-form solution for the homogeneous equation, and one has to use either a numerical method, or an approximation method such as Magnus expansion.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] Knowing the matrix U, the general solution of the non-homogeneous equation is $\mathbf {y} (x)=U(x)\mathbf {y_{0}} +U(x)\int U^{-1}(x)\mathbf {b} (x)\,dx,$ where the column matrix $\mathbf {y_{0}}$ is an arbitrary constant of integration.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] A linear ordinary equation of order one with variable coefficients may be solved by quadrature, which means that the solutions may be expressed in terms of integrals.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] This is not the case for order at least two.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] This is the main result of Picard–Vessiot theory which was initiated by Émile Picard and Ernest Vessiot, and whose recent developments are called differential Galois theory.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] The impossibility of solving by quadrature can be compared with the Abel–Ruffini theorem, which states that an algebraic equation of degree at least five cannot, in general, be solved by radicals.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] This analogy extends to the proof methods and motivates the denomination of differential Galois theory.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] Similarly to the algebraic case, the theory allows deciding which equations may be solved by quadrature, and if possible solving them.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] However, for both theories, the necessary computations are extremely difficult, even with the most powerful computers.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] Nevertheless, the case of order two with rational coefficients has been completely solved by Kovacic's algorithm.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] Cauchy–Euler equations are examples of equations of any order, with variable coefficients, that can be solved explicitly.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] A holonomic function, also called a *D-finite function*, is a function that is a solution of a homogeneous linear differential equation with polynomial coefficients.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] Most functions that are commonly considered in mathematics are holonomic or quotients of holonomic functions.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] In fact, holonomic functions include polynomials, algebraic functions, logarithm, exponential function, sine, cosine, hyperbolic sine, hyperbolic cosine, inverse trigonometric and inverse hyperbolic functions, and many special functions such as Bessel functions and hypergeometric functions.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] Holonomic functions have several closure properties; in particular, sums, products, derivative and integrals of holonomic functions are holonomic.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] Moreover, these closure properties are effective, in the sense that there are algorithms for computing the differential equation of the result of any of these operations, knowing the differential equations of the input.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] Usefulness of the concept of holonomic functions results of Zeilberger's theorem, which follows.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] A *holonomic sequence* is a sequence of numbers that may be generated by a recurrence relation with polynomial coefficients.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] The coefficients of the Taylor series at a point of a holonomic function form a holonomic sequence.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] Conversely, if the sequence of the coefficients of a power series is holonomic, then the series defines a holonomic function (even if the radius of convergence is zero).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/linear-differential-equation] There are efficient algorithms for both conversions, that is for computing the recurrence relation from the differential equation, and *vice versa*.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/ordinary-differential-equation] In mathematics, an **ordinary differential equation** (**ODE**) is a differential equation (DE) dependent on only a single independent variable.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/ordinary-differential-equation] As with any other DE, its unknown(s) consists of one (or more) function(s) and involves the derivatives of those functions.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/ordinary-differential-equation] The term "ordinary" is used in contrast with *partial* differential equations (PDEs) which may be with respect to *more than* one independent variable, and, less commonly, in contrast with *stochastic* differential equations (SDEs) where the modeled process is random.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/ordinary-differential-equation] where $a_{0}(x),\ldots ,a_{n}(x)$ and $b(x)$ are arbitrary differentiable functions that do not need to be linear, and $y',\ldots ,y^{(n)}$ are the successive derivatives of the unknown function y of the variable x .
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/ordinary-differential-equation] Among ordinary differential equations, linear differential equations play a prominent role for several reasons.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/ordinary-differential-equation] Most elementary and special functions that are encountered in physics and applied mathematics are solutions of linear differential equations (see Holonomic function).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/ordinary-differential-equation] When physical phenomena are modeled with non-linear equations, they are generally approximated by linear differential equations for an easier solution.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/ordinary-differential-equation] The few non-linear ODEs that can be solved explicitly are generally solved by transforming the equation into an equivalent linear ODE (see, for example Riccati equation).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/ordinary-differential-equation] Some ODEs can be solved explicitly in terms of known functions and integrals.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/ordinary-differential-equation] When that is not possible, the equation for computing the Taylor series of the solutions may be useful.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/ordinary-differential-equation] For applied problems, numerical methods for ordinary differential equations can supply an approximation of the solution.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/ordinary-differential-equation] Ordinary differential equations (ODEs) arise in many contexts of mathematics and social and natural sciences.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/ordinary-differential-equation] Mathematical descriptions of change use differentials and derivatives.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/ordinary-differential-equation] Various differentials, derivatives, and functions become related via equations, such that a differential equation is a result that describes dynamically changing phenomena, evolution, and variation.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/ordinary-differential-equation] Often, quantities are defined as the rate of change of other quantities (for example, derivatives of displacement with respect to time), or gradients of quantities, which is how they enter differential equations.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/ordinary-differential-equation] Specific mathematical fields include geometry and analytical mechanics.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/ordinary-differential-equation] Many mathematicians have studied differential equations and contributed to the field, including Newton, Leibniz, the Bernoulli family, Riccati, Clairaut, d'Alembert, and Euler.
