[src:ordinary-differential-equations/ordinary-differential-equation] The differential equations are in their equivalent and alternative forms that lead to the solution through integration.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/ordinary-differential-equation] When all other methods for solving an ODE fail, or in the cases where we have some intuition about what the solution to a DE might look like, it is sometimes possible to solve a DE simply by guessing the solution and validating it is correct.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/ordinary-differential-equation] To use this method, we simply guess a solution to the differential equation, and then plug the solution into the differential equation to verify whether it satisfies the equation.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/ordinary-differential-equation] If it does then we have a particular solution to the DE, otherwise we start over again and try another guess.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/ordinary-differential-equation] For instance we could guess that the solution to a DE has the form: $y=Ae^{i\alpha t}$ since this is a very common solution that physically behaves in a sinusoidal way.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/ordinary-differential-equation] In the case of a first order ODE that is non-homogeneous we need to first find a solution to the homogeneous portion of the DE, otherwise known as the associated homogeneous equation, and then find a solution to the entire non-homogeneous equation by guessing.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/phase-portrait] In mathematics, a **phase portrait** is a geometric representation of the orbits of a dynamical system in the phase plane.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/phase-portrait] Each set of initial conditions is represented by a different point or curve.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/phase-portrait] Phase portraits are an invaluable tool in studying dynamical systems.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/phase-portrait] They consist of a plot of typical trajectories in the phase space.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/phase-portrait] This reveals information such as whether an attractor, a repellor or limit cycle is present for the chosen parameter value.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/phase-portrait] The concept of topological equivalence is important in classifying the behaviour of systems by specifying when two different phase portraits represent the same qualitative dynamic behavior.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/phase-portrait] An attractor is a stable point which is also called a "sink".
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/phase-portrait] The repeller is considered as an unstable point, which is also known as a "source".
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/phase-portrait] A phase portrait graph of a dynamical system depicts the system's trajectories (with arrows) and stable steady states (with dots) and unstable steady states (with circles) in a phase space.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/phase-portrait] A phase portrait represents the directional behavior of a system of ordinary differential equations (ODEs).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/phase-portrait] The phase portrait can indicate the stability of the system.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/phase-portrait] The phase portrait behavior of a system of ODEs can be determined by the eigenvalues or the trace and determinant (trace = λ1 + λ2, determinant = λ1λ2) of the system.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] This theory is important in applied mathematics, where Sturm–Liouville problems occur very frequently, particularly when dealing with separable linear partial differential equations.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] For example, in quantum mechanics, the one-dimensional time-independent Schrödinger equation is a Sturm–Liouville problem.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] Sturm–Liouville theory is named after Jacques Charles François Sturm (1803–1855) and Joseph Liouville (1809–1882), who developed the theory.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] on a finite interval $[a,b]$ that is "regular".
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] The function $w=w(x)$ , sometimes denoted $r=r(x)$ , is called the *weight* or *density* function.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] For a regular Sturm–Liouville problem, a function $y=y(x)$ is called a *solution* if it is continuously differentiable and satisfies the equation (**1**) at every $x\in (a,b)$ .
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] In the case of more general $p,q,w$ , the solutions must be understood in a weak sense.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] The terms eigenvalue and eigenvector are used because the solutions correspond to the eigenvalues and eigenfunctions of a Hermitian differential operator in an appropriate Hilbert space of functions with inner product defined using the weight function.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] Sturm–Liouville theory studies the existence and asymptotic behavior of the eigenvalues, the corresponding qualitative theory of the eigenfunctions and their completeness in the function space.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] Some classical results may be established about the oscillation and non-oscillation properties of solutions to certain Sturm-Liouville problems.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] In particular these establish that linearly independent solutions oscillate "equally rapidly" and the conditions under which solutions oscillate more rapidly.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] It can be shown that there are no non-trivial solutions to the above equation which have infinitely many zeros on some closed interval ${\textstyle (a,b)}$ .
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] If ${\textstyle x_{1},x_{2}}$ are two consecutive zeros of ${\textstyle u}$ , then ${\textstyle v}$ is zero somewhere on the interval ${\textstyle (x_{1},x_{2})}$ .
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] *In particular if ${\textstyle v}$* is zero whenever ${\textstyle u}$ is zero, v oscillates more rapidly than ${\textstyle u}$ .
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] The differential equation (**1**) is said to be in **Sturm–Liouville form** or **self-adjoint form**.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] The mapping defined by: $Lu=-{\frac {1}{w(x)}}\left({\frac {d}{dx}}\left[p(x)\,{\frac {du}{dx}}\right]+q(x)u\right)$ can be viewed as a linear operator L mapping a function u to another function Lu, and it can be studied in the context of functional analysis.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] This is precisely the eigenvalue problem; that is, one seeks eigenvalues *λ*1, *λ*2, *λ*3,... and the corresponding eigenvectors *u*1, *u*2, *u*3,... of the L operator.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] In this space L is defined on sufficiently smooth functions which satisfy the above regular boundary conditions.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] This can be seen formally by using integration by parts twice, where the boundary terms vanish by virtue of the boundary conditions.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] It then follows that the eigenvalues of a Sturm–Liouville operator are real and that eigenfunctions of L corresponding to different eigenvalues are orthogonal.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] However, this operator is unbounded and hence existence of an orthonormal basis of eigenfunctions is not evident.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] To overcome this problem, one looks at the resolvent $\left(L-z\right)^{-1},\qquad z\in \mathbb {R} ,$ where z is not an eigenvalue.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] Then, computing the resolvent amounts to solving a nonhomogeneous equation, which can be done using the variation of parameters formula.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] This shows that the resolvent is an integral operator with a continuous symmetric kernel (the Green's function of the problem).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] As a consequence of the Arzelà–Ascoli theorem, this integral operator is compact and existence of a sequence of eigenvalues αn which converge to 0 and eigenfunctions which form an orthonormal basis follows from the spectral theorem for compact operators.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] Finally, note that $\left(L-z\right)^{-1}u=\alpha u,\qquad Lu=\left(z+\alpha ^{-1}\right)u,$ are equivalent, so we may take $\lambda =z+\alpha ^{-1}$ with the same eigenfunctions.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] If the interval is unbounded, or if the coefficients have singularities at the boundary points, one calls L singular.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] In this case, the spectrum no longer consists of eigenvalues alone and can contain a continuous component.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] There is still an associated eigenfunction expansion (similar to Fourier series versus Fourier transform).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] This is important in quantum mechanics, since the one-dimensional time-independent Schrödinger equation is a special case of a Sturm–Liouville equation.
