[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] The second of these equations can be analytically solved once the eigenvalues are known.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] The Sturm–Liouville differential equation (**1**) with boundary conditions may be solved analytically, which can be exact or provide an approximation, by the Rayleigh–Ritz method, or by the matrix-variational method of Gerck et al.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] Numerically, a variety of methods are also available.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] In difficult cases, one may need to carry out the intermediate calculations to several hundred decimal places of accuracy in order to obtain the eigenvalues correctly to a few decimal places.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] This strategy is not applicable for locating complex eigenvalues.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] Further, all solutions are linear combinations of these two solutions.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] In the SPPS algorithm, one must begin with an arbitrary value *λ*∗ 0 (often *λ*∗ 0 = 0; it does not need to be an eigenvalue) and any solution *y*0 of (**1**) with *λ* = *λ*∗ 0 which does not vanish on [*a*,*b*].
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] (Discussion below of ways to find appropriate *y*0 and *λ*∗ 0.) Two sequences of functions *X*(*n*)(*t*), *X̃*(*n*)(*t*) on [*a*,*b*], referred to as *iterated integrals*, are defined recursively as follows.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] First when *n* = 0, they are taken to be identically equal to 1 on [*a*,*b*].
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] Next one chooses coefficients *c*0 and *c*1 so that the combination *y* = *c*0*u*0 + *c*1*u*1 satisfies the first boundary condition (**2**).
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] The values of *X*(*n*)(*b*) and *X̃*(*n*)(*b*) provide the values of *u*0(*b*) and *u*1(*b*) and the derivatives *u*′0(*b*) and *u*′0(*b*), so the second boundary condition (**3**) becomes an equation in a power series in λ.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] For numerical work one may truncate this series to a finite number of terms, producing a calculable polynomial in λ whose roots are approximations of the sought-after eigenvalues.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] When *λ* = *λ*0, this reduces to the original construction described above for a solution linearly independent to a given one.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] The representations (**5**) and (**6**) also have theoretical applications in Sturm–Liouville theory.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] The SPPS method can, itself, be used to find a starting solution *y*0.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] Consider the equation (*py*′)′ = *μqy*; i.e., q, w, and λ are replaced in (**1**) by 0, −*q*, and μ respectively.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] Then the constant function 1 is a nonvanishing solution corresponding to the eigenvalue *μ*0 = 0.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] While there is no guarantee that *u*0 or *u*1 will not vanish, the complex function *y*0 = *u*0 + *iu*1 will never vanish because two linearly-independent solutions of a regular Sturm–Liouville equation cannot vanish simultaneously as a consequence of the Sturm separation theorem.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] This trick gives a solution *y*0 of (**1**) for the value *λ*0 = 0.
[src:ordinary-differential-equations/sturm-liouville-theory] In practice if (**1**) has real coefficients, the solutions based on *y*0 will have very small imaginary parts which must be discarded.
